What have the romans has plotnine ever give us in Python?¶

To get started I found this tutorial super useful.

Here is a more comprehensive, super-useful tutorial (by Jeroen Janssens, author of plotnine) on the library especially for those who already worked with ggplot.

Also have a look at the graph gallery - a real eyecandy!

Our database contains info about over 50,000 diamonds, of which we'll use cut, carat, color, clarity and price for plotting. You can find further information on the DB.

Let's try some basic plotting, with easy coloring¶

In [182]:
# import necessary functions to build the following plot
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_violin, theme_light

(
    ggplot(diamonds)  # What data to use
    + aes(x="cut", y= "price", fill = "cut")  # What variable to use, including the variable for fillcolor
    + geom_violin()  # Geometric object to use for drawing
    + theme_light() # to make it clearer
    
)
Out[182]:
<ggplot: (8773679977828)>

The lesson: most diamonds are actually cheap!

Histogram for count values, with flipping for more clarity and a bonus theme¶

In [183]:
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_bar, coord_flip, theme_xkcd, labs

(
ggplot(diamonds) 
    + aes(x="cut") 
    + geom_bar() 
    + coord_flip()
    + labs(title = "Counting how many diamonds are in each cut-group")
    + theme_xkcd()
)
Out[183]:
<ggplot: (8773678858719)>

Boxplots and violinplots: the most informative plot to inspect the distribution of the data¶

In [176]:
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, stat_bin, geom_boxplot, theme_minimal, geom_violin

(
ggplot(diamonds) 
    + aes(x="clarity", y= "price") 
    + geom_boxplot()
    + geom_violin(aes(fill="clarity"))
    + labs(fill="Clarity class", 
          x = "")
    + theme_minimal()
)

Clarity and cut: relationship with price?¶

In [186]:
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, labs, geom_jitter, theme_minimal

(
    ggplot(diamonds)
    + aes(x="clarity", y="cut", color="price")
    + labs(title="", y="")
    + geom_jitter(alpha = 0.2, size = 0.1)
    + theme_minimal()
)
Out[186]:
<ggplot: (8773680244598)>

The plot above is not very informative in this case, because we have too many datapoints in each cells. However, one can see that S1 and especially S2 clarities are the most popular. Very clear diamonds tend to be cut ideally - no suprises there... The relation to price is difficult to see, because most diamonds are within the cheaper range. Let's go further.

Faceting on 2 categorical variables: clarity and cut to see their relationship with a continuous variable (price)¶

In [189]:
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, facet_grid, labs, geom_point, theme_minimal, theme, element_text

(
    ggplot(diamonds)
    + facet_grid(facets="cut~color")
    + aes(x="clarity", y="price", color = "price")
    + geom_point()
    + labs(
        x="Clarity",
        y="Price",
        title="Price of the diamond, given cut and clarity",
        )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=90, hjust=1)) # rotate x labels to improve readibility
    
)
Out[189]:
<ggplot: (8773679994435)>

We start seeing that ideal cut diamonds tend to be expensive, especially in the mid-clarity region, wheareas fair cut are a good deal cheaper.

Finally, my favourite visualisation of this dataset, turboed with prediction lines¶

In [190]:
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, theme_minimal, coord_cartesian

(
ggplot(diamonds)
    + aes("carat", "price", color = "clarity")
    + geom_point(alpha = 0.3, size = 0.7) # make points opaque to better account for overlap
    + geom_smooth(stat="smooth") # GLM-based prediction line with 95% CI
    + labs(
        title = "Diamond prices based on clarity and carat", 
        x = "Carat", 
        y = "Price of diamond", 
        color = "Clarity")
    + coord_cartesian(xlim = [0, 4], ylim = [0, 20000]) 
    + theme_minimal()
    
)
Out[190]:
<ggplot: (8773665049613)>

The clarity of the diamond seems to be a strong predictor of the price, with clear (IF, "internally flawless") diamonds being the most expensive. Note the uneven distribution of carat, which can be tricky in ML models (floor effect around integers and halves).

And if you wanted to see the above plot but separately by cut:

In [181]:
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, theme_minimal, coord_cartesian, facet_wrap

(
ggplot(diamonds)
    + aes("carat", "price", color = "clarity")
    + geom_point(alpha = 0.3, size = 0.3) # make points opaque to better account for overlap
    + geom_smooth(stat="smooth") # GLM-based prediction line with 95% CI. Interestingly, plotnine appears to provide an "overall" prediction line (ggplot provides a point-by-point, curvy solution)
    + labs(
        title = "Diamond prices based on clarity and carat", 
        x = "Carat", 
        y = "Price of diamond", 
        color = "Clarity")
    + coord_cartesian(xlim = [0, 4], ylim = [0, 20000]) 
    + facet_wrap("cut")
    + theme_minimal()
    
)
Out[181]:
<ggplot: (8773676432107)>
